    <section>
<h1>Objects</h1>
<h2>Objects are special kind of data. They are so important that we put them into separate article.</h2>
<ul><li>Part 1:	<a href='./basic-syntax'>Basic Syntax</a></li><li>Part 2:	Objects</li><li>Part 3:	<a href='./functions'>Functions</a></li><li>Part 4:	<a href='./alternative-syntax'>Alternative Syntax</a></li><li>Part 5:	<a href='./use-case'>Use Case</a></li></ul>
</section>

<section>
<h3>Introduction</h3>
You can start thinking about them as a dictionary, where by some key you can get value.

<pre><code class='language-javascript'>
//create dictionary with 2 elements
let englishToGerman = {"Hi": "Hallo", "Beer": "Bier"};
//add individual element
englishToGerman["Umbrella"] = "Regenschirm";
//change individual element
englishToGerman["Umbrella"] = "Schirm";
//access individual element
console.log(englishToGerman["Umbrella"]);
</code></pre>
</section>

<section>
<h3>More complex example</h3>
The real power comes when you understand how you can put complex structures as values

<pre><code class='language-javascript'>
let person = {
    "firstName": "Bob", //string -> string
    lastName: "Allan",  //alternative declaration: no brackets around key
    age: 23,            //string -> digit
    relatives: {        //string -> object
        brother: "Peter",
        mother: "Kate"
    },
    greetings: (address) => {   //string -> function
        return "Aloha " + address
    }
};

//Accessing field
console.log(person["firstName"]);    //-> "Bob"
//Alternative syntax to access field
console.log(person.age);    //-> 23
console.log(person.greetings("John"));    //-> "Aloha John
</code></pre>
</section>


<section>
<h3>Homework</h3>
To practice you can describe some legal document like driving license as an javascript object.
</section>
